Docker Volumes


Problem: container data is ephemaral 

data written inside a containers normal writable layer is lost when the container is removed.

docker run -d --name voltest ubuntu sleep 300
docker exec -it voltest bash
echo "hello from container" > /data.txt
cat /data.txt
exit
docker rm -f voltest
docker run -d --name voltest ubuntu sleep 300
docker exec -it voltest bash
cat /data.txt

Result:

file does not exist.
This proves container filesystem data is ephemaral.

Creating a docker volume:

>>List volume:
docker volume ls

Create a volume:

docker volume create mydata

docker volume ls

>>Mounting a volume into a container:

Run a container with the volume mounted:

docker run -d --name voltest -v mydata:/data ubuntu sleep 300

Meaning:

mydata → Docker-managed volume
/data  → mount path inside container

Creating a file insdie the mounted volume:

docker exec -it voltest bash
echo "persistent file" > /data/test.txt
cat /data/test.txt
exit


Peristence across container deletion:

docker rm -f voltest

Started a new container with:

docker run -d --name voltest2 -v mydata:/data ubuntu sleep 300

checking the file with :

docker exec -it voltest2 bash
cat /data/test.txt

Result file is available!
This proves volume data survives container deletion.

Meaning of docker rm -f 

-f means force remove.

behaviour:

running container → force stop → remove
stopped container → remove

without -f, docker removes only stopped containers.

Inspecting a volume:

docker volume inspect mydata

important fields:

Name
Driver
Mountpoint

Mountpoint shows where Docker stores the volume data on the host.


Key concept:

container lifecycle ≠ volume lifecycle

Containers can be removed and recreated, while volume data remains.























